2026-07-14 FOUNDATION: taxonomy + 27 seed companies + chokepoint hypotheses + sources.
2026-07-16 FIX: chokepoint column normalized from TRUE/FALSE to yes/no. Not cosmetic. The artifact template tests c.chokepoint==='yes', so every chokepoint in this map would have rendered as NOT a chokepoint the moment the map was built, showing "0 chokepoints flagged" with no error raised. Six of the nine foundations had this drift (different research agents wrote different vocabularies); the four others were already yes/no. Counts preserved exactly. Now enforced by tools/gate.sh.
2026-07-16 RELATIONSHIPS BURST (first edges on this map): 14 sourced edges merged, 0 -> 14. Method: 3 paced Sonnet workers to staging files, then EVERY cited URL refetched independently by tools/verify_edges.py (14/14 reachable, both endpoints named, zero fabricated URLs, zero landing pages), then merged by tools/merge_edges.py.
  THE ROUTE THAT MADE THIS POSSIBLE: all 5 of this map's chokepoints are Chinese A-share filers (Shanghai/Shenzhen, Chinese-language), so their own filings are effectively unreachable. But their edges are disclosed IN ENGLISH by their Western counterparties: MP Materials' 10-K documents Shenghe, SQM's 20-F documents Tianqi, Vale's 20-F documents Huayou, Pilbara's ASX release documents Ganfeng. SOURCE THE CHINA EDGE FROM THE COUNTERPARTY'S SIDE. Same shape as the toolbox's paywalled-spec route: when the primary source is unreachable, find the document that describes it from the other side.
  BEST EDGE: Tianqi is simultaneously SQM's COMPETITOR and its ~21.9% shareholder with the right to choose up to three SQM board members, and Chilean law limits SQM's ability to withhold competitively sensitive information from a director. Verified by hand in the 20-F. The worker had the stake and seats right but MISSED that the same filing discloses Tianqi selling down (all Series B gone, board-approved Series A disposal takes it to ~20.65%); added by hand. A worker's honest, correct fact can still be an incomplete one.
  DISAGREEMENT WAS THE FINDING: worker 1 wrote "Energy Fuels competes-with Lynas" tier 1; worker 2 independently examined an Energy Fuels 10-K, saw only a stock-performance peer-group chart, and REJECTED that same edge as too weak. Adjudicated at the source: worker 1 was RIGHT (the FY2024 10-K says plainly "Outside of China, there are a few groups processing monazite for rare earths. These include Energy Fuels, Lynas ... and the Saskatchewan Research Council"); worker 2 read a different filing year and generalised from the weaker of two mentions. Both agents were honest; only the document settled it.
  HONEST WEAKNESSES, do not oversell this burst: (1) only 6 of 14 edges are real dependencies; 8 are competes-with, which the README explicitly says is NOT the payoff. 01 by comparison is 29% competes-with, this is 57%. (2) The Glencore -> Umicore cobalt edge rests on a 2019-05-29 press release, by far the oldest evidence here and tier 2; Glencore's Mutanda mine was idled shortly after it was published, so that edge needs refreshing before anyone leans on it. (3) Zero edges found for Syrah: its real offtakes (Tesla, Ford, LG, Posco) are all outside this map's company list, which is a scope question for the map, not a research failure. (4) Lynas names NO commercial customer in its own annual report, only the US DoD.
  NEXT: financials for the 5 chokepoints (all Chinese filers, so expect tier 2/3 and say so), and refresh the Glencore edge.
2026-07-16 SCOPE DECISION + RENDERER: this map now RENDERS (artifact/critical-minerals-map.html), the first map other than 01 that can.
  SCOPE, decided on the repo's own precedent rather than taste: a Keystone map DOES admit its downstream buyers as nodes. 01-semiconductor already carries GM, BMW, Lenovo and HP as `oem`, and 11 of its 48 edges touch a system firm. GM and BMW in a chip map are exactly analogous to Tesla and Ford here. So Syrah's offtakes were never out of scope, my company list was just too short. Added 6 downstream nodes (Tesla Inc, Ford Motor Company, Lucid Group, LG Energy Solution, Samsung SDI, POSCO Future M) with blank financials, which the gate's incomplete-does-not-fail rule accepts as honest.
  MEASURED FIRST, then built (the spike was worth ~3 minutes): running 01's builder against 02's data succeeded with EXIT 0 and rendered a map where 30 of 33 companies landed in NO layer, because 01's LAYERS are hardcoded to semiconductor roles (ip-eda, foundry, osat) and this map's roles are miner/refiner/separator. It did not crash. A map-specific renderer fails SILENTLY on another map's data, same shape as the chokepoint bug. That measurement is now a permanent selftest fixture in shared/build_map.py.
  02's map.json declares an 11-layer minerals taxonomy (miner -> trader -> refiner -> separator -> chemicals -> anode/cathode -> magnets -> cells -> recyclers -> oem). Zero orphans. Verified in a real browser: 33 companies, 14 relationships, 5 chokepoints, value chain populated (Miners 21, Traders 2, Refiners 19, Separators 4), all 8 tabs, no JS errors, and storage key `critical-minerals-map:v1` is DISTINCT from `semiconductor-map:v1` so the two maps cannot clobber each other's watchlist. It also inherited durable-state v2.0.0 for free.
  NEXT: financials for the 5 chokepoints (Chinese A-share filers, expect tier 2/3 and label them so), refresh the stale 2019 Glencore edge, and publish this map as its own artifact.
